;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 19 Sep 2012 10:16:41 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"General";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"conference";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"smashing magazine";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/?p=8614";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8334:"<a
href='http://rss.buysellads.com/click.php?z=1260586&k=bd32b265e46b660b3d64f818ce58f2d8&a=8614&c=248497900' target='_blank'><img
src='http://rss.buysellads.com/img.php?z=1260586&k=bd32b265e46b660b3d64f818ce58f2d8&a=8614&c=248497900' border='0' alt='' /></a><p>I&#8217;ve had a <em>very</em> pleasant few days in Germany. Good food, good beer, beautiful surroundings, and more web designers and developers than you can shake a Volkswagen at. Smashing Magazine have done a fantastic job of hosting <a
href="http://smashingconf.com/">their first ever conference</a>!</p><p><span
id="more-8614"></span></p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/main-venue.jpg" alt="" /><br
/>The Main Venue <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/17/smashing-conference-liveblog-reporting-day-1/">Photo by SmashingMagazine</a></div><p>Monday morning kicked off with (coffee, obviously) name tags, goody bags and plenty of anticipation as the audience awaited the first speaker. I was situated more or less in the middle of everything. The seat next to me was empty and I was a little surprised when <a
href="https://twitter.com/ia">Oliver Reichenstein</a> sat in it. What do you say to a typographical design icon, whose work you&#8217;ve been drooling over for years? I came up with:</p><blockquote><p>Couldn&#8217;t you get a seat at the front?</p></blockquote><p>Brilliant, Ian.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/ia.jpg" alt="" /><br
/>Oliver Reichenstein on stage <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/17/smashing-conference-liveblog-reporting-day-1/">Photo by SmashingMagazine</a></div><p>But that&#8217;s what happens at conferences where speakers and audience can mingle and talk &#8211; all the big names were available and approachable.</p><hr
/><h2>Speakers</h2><p>The line up of speakers was very impressive. Sixteen in total, delivering talks on web design business, technology, technique, theory, workflow and everything in between. Here&#8217;s a quick breakdown:</p><ul><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/adactio">Jeremy Keith</a>, who you&#8217;ll know from so many things, not least of which his book <a
href="http://html5forwebdesigners.com/">HTML5 for Web Designers</a>.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/rachelandrew">Rachel Andrew</a> CMS guru and the brains behind <a
href="http://grabaperch.com/">Perch</a>.</li><li><a
href="http://fr.twitter.com/stephenhay">Stephen Hay</a> Designer. Developer. Funny guy.</li><li><a
href="https://twitter.com/ia">Oliver Reichenstein</a> <em>The</em> <a
href="http://informationarchitects.net/">Information Architect</a> and the man behind <a
href="https://twitter.com/iawriter">iA Writer</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/stubbornella">Nicole Sullivan</a> Self proclaimed Geek, initiator of <a
href="http://oocss.org/">OOCSS</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/boagworld">Paul Boag</a> Mr.<a
href="http://boagworld.com/">Boagworld</a> and expert on handling clients.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/jaffathecake">Jake Archibald</a> Bafflingly clever Developer at <a
href="http://lanyrd.com/">Lanyrd</a>.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/markboulton">Mark Boulton</a> If you&#8217;ve delved into grids, you&#8217;ll have come across Mark&#8217;s work. Currently busy with <a
href="https://gridsetapp.com/">Gridsetapp</a>.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/Malarkey">Andy Clarke</a> The man whose CSS course first got me away from table-based layouts, recently redesigned <a
href="http://stuffandnonsense.co.uk/">his site</a> with typical Mod flair.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/LeaVerou">Lea Verou</a> CSS genius and heading away from the speaking scene due to her new position as Developer Relations at W3C</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/jbrewer">Josh Brewer</a> Principal Designer at Twitter and the guy behind (the awesome) <a
href="http://52weeksofux.com/">52 Weeks of UX</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/TimAhrens">Tim Ahrens</a> Typographer known for his work with TypeKit and <a
href="http://justanotherfoundry.com/">Just Another Foundry</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/snookca">Johnathan Snook</a> Entertaining guy who once worked with Yahoo and can now be found busying himself with <a
href="http://smacss.com/">SMACSS</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/brad_frost">Brad Frost</a> The man of the moment in RWD, outspoken, insightful, good bloke.</li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/aarron">Aarron Walter</a> Inspiring and calmly creative, Director of UX at <a
href="http://mailchimp.com/">MailChimp</a></li><li><a
href="http://twitter.com/codepo8">Christian Heilmann</a> As firey on stage as in his appearance, Developer Evangelist for Mozilla.</li></ul><p>Not bad, right?</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><blockquote
class="twitter-tweet" lang="fr"><p>SET SAIL FOR FAIL:My phone ringing during my <a
href="https://twitter.com/search/%23smashingconf">#smashingconf</a> talk.With my Nyan Cat ringtone.Thankfully, the audience was very cool folks :)</p><p>&mdash; Lea Verou (@LeaVerou) <a
href="https://twitter.com/LeaVerou/status/248012995244994560" data-datetime="2012-09-18T10:58:00+00:00">Septembre 18, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><p>(I wouldn&#8217;t worry Lea &#8211; we&#8217;re all human after all!)</div><hr
/><h2>Organizers</h2><p>Smashing Magazine have a great team &#8211; always friendly, always helpful, and their energy carried the whole event on perfectly. Let&#8217;s face it, sixteen hours of talks in two days is pretty intense, but the atmosphere made sucking up all the information a breeze.</p><p>Saying that, the conference wouldn&#8217;t have been what it was without <a
href="https://twitter.com/marcthiele">Marc Thiele</a> and <a
href="http://twitter.com/smashingmag">Vitaly Friedman</a>. Marc, who&#8217;s found a niche in organizing web events (check out <a
href="http://2012.beyondtellerrand.com/">Beyond Tellerand</a> if you&#8217;re in Germany later this year) is the stage presence and social animal needed for the job. Vitaly, is the heart and soul of Smashing Magazine, famously friendly, and it was great to grab a beer and a chat with him on the closing night.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/P1010317.jpg" alt=""/><br
/>Vitaly and Marc <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/18/smashing-conference-liveblog-day-2/">Photo by SmashingMagazine</a></div><p>My original plan was to write a post, summarizing some of the things I&#8217;ve learned here. But that&#8217;s not going to work &#8211; I&#8217;ve learned too much! Instead, you can expect some articles and tutorials which give some of my favorite tips and tricks the attention they deserve. Stay tuned for that..</p><p>In the meantime, you can check out the <a
href="https://twitter.com/i/#!/search/realtime/%23smashingconf">#smashingconf</a> hashtag on Twitter, or the <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/17/smashing-conference-liveblog-reporting-day-1/">summary</a> <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/18/smashing-conference-liveblog-day-2/">posts</a> over on Smashing Magazine.</p><hr
/><p>Smashing Magazine and Envato share many of the same values, so it&#8217;s always a pleasure to see Vitaly&#8217;s projects thrive. Smashingconf 2012 was a winner and whenever the next one happens (and it will) you need to get your name signed up as quick as you can &#8211; tickets will be snapped up faster than a new batch of smoked Black Forest sausages!</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/audience.png" alt="" title="audience"/><br
/>Spellbound <a
href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2012/09/18/smashing-conference-liveblog-day-2/">Photo by SmashingMagazine</a></div>
