;s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Visuals";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"animation";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3:"gif";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"loader";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"photoshop";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"pre-loader";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/?p=8542";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16089:"<a
href='http://rss.buysellads.com/click.php?z=1260586&k=bd32b265e46b660b3d64f818ce58f2d8&a=8542&c=2072817879' target='_blank'><img
src='http://rss.buysellads.com/img.php?z=1260586&k=bd32b265e46b660b3d64f818ce58f2d8&a=8542&c=2072817879' border='0' alt='' /></a><p>Let&#8217;s create an animated pre-loader gif for your next UI project. You&#8217;ll need the Extended version Photoshop CS3 or above.</p><p><span
id="more-8542"></span></p><p>We&#8217;re going to create a little animated gif that can be used for a multitude of widgets, anytime ajax content is being requested, files are being uploaded, whatever you fancy.  Feel free to mix-in your own styles and variations to the loader as we go along.  There are three major sections we&#8217;ll be undertaking:</p><ul><li>Creating the Loader Shapes<li>Styling the Loader Shapes<li>Animating the Loader</ul><p>Ready. Set. Go..</p><hr
/><h2><span>Step 1: Creating Shapes</span> Setup File</h2><p>Begin by setting up the canvas size, and add a quick background to get started.</p><ol><li>New Photoshop Document (File>New) || Control/Command + N</li><li>Canvas size: 100px by 100px</li><li>Double click BG layer, Convert to regular layer</li><li>Set its color to dark gray, I used: #3d3d3d</li></ol><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.42.55 PM.jpg" width="195" height="181" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.42.55 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 2: Creating Shapes</span> Background Pattern</h2><p>Just for kicks, we&#8217;ll add a lined pattern to our background, and then start work on the loader.</p><p>Create a new transparent document: (7px by 7px). Draw a diagonal line with a 1px black pencil tool (click the top left pixel, hold down shift and click the bottom right pixel)</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.43.00 PM.jpg" width="195" height="181" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.43.00 PM"></div><p>Define and name the pattern (Edit menu > Define Pattern).</p><p>That done, jump back to the original document and create a layer style of &#8220;Pattern Overlay&#8221; on our gray background layer: (Layer menu > Layer Style > Pattern Overlay). Choose your pattern from the pattern box, and lower the opacity (I used 20%).</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.45.21 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.45.21 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 3: Creating Shapes</span> Guides</h2><p>We&#8217;re going to set up a few marks which will act as guides to help us along &#8211; we&#8217;ll use the &#8220;Transform Again&#8221; Command to speed things up.</p><p>Draw a 1px vertical white line with the line tool on your document:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 6.04.26 PM.jpg" width="288" height="196" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 6.04.26 PM"></div><p>To make sure it&#8217;s aligned in the center, select both its layer and the background layer, grab the move tool, and click the &#8220;Align Horizontal Centers&#8221; option like so:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.47.15 PM.jpg" width="290" height="247" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.47.15 PM"></div><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.47.10 PM.jpg" width="154" height="46" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.47.10 PM"></div><p>Rotate the line 45&deg; (Select the line Edit menu> Free Transform || Control/Command + T)</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.47.35 PM.jpg" width="418" height="36" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.47.35 PM"></div><p>Select Edit menu > Transform > &#8220;Transform Again&#8221; while holding down the &#8220;Option/Alt&#8221; Key (Command/Control + Option/Alt + Shift + T )</p><p>Perform that command several times until the line has rotated all the way around, like so:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.48.16 PM.jpg" width="220" height="188" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.48.16 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 4: Creating Shapes</span> Tick Marks</h2><p>Using the same technique as explained above, we&#8217;re going to add some little tick marks on each grid line to make the loader go round and round..  Here goes.</p><p>Add some guides around where you want your initial &#8220;Tick Mark&#8221; to appear (make sure your guides are on whole pixels, don&#8217;t split pixels).</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.54.38 PM.jpg" width="285" height="211" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.54.38 PM"></div><p>Create a rounded rectangle with a 1px radius within our guide lines (make sure you have snapping turned on for guides: View menu > Snap)</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.53.50 PM.jpg" width="429" height="408" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.53.50 PM"></div><p>Using the Direct Selection Tool move the bottom corners (nodes) of our rectangle tick shape inwards, so the shape tapers.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 12.59.00 PM copy.jpg" width="594" height="515" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 12.59.00 PM"></div><p>Utilize the same &#8216;Transform Again&#8217; trick we used above, to duplicate the shape all the way around our tick marks (When rotating the 45&deg; be sure to set the transformation point to the center of our grid, not the center of the rectangle tick shape, which it where it defaults).</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.00.32 PM.jpg" width="594" height="515" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.00.32 PM"></div><p>Select Edit menu > Transform > &#8220;Transform Again&#8221; while holding down the &#8220;Option/Alt&#8221; Key (Command/Control + Option/Alt + Shift + T ) until the tick has been copied all the way around. It should look like this:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.01.24 PM.jpg" width="290" height="224" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.01.24 PM"></div><p>Layer Check: ensure your layers panel looks like this:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.01.10 PM.jpg" width="284" height="286" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.01.10 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 1: Styling Shapes</span> Build Our Tick Marks</h2><p>Phew.  We&#8217;ve got the pre loader shapes all created, now we&#8217;re just going to add a bunch of layer styles to spruce things up a bit.  As usual, salt to taste.  We&#8217;re going to be adding layer styles which can all be found in &#8220;Layer menu > Layer Styles&#8221;.</p><p>Add a &#8220;Color Overlay&#8221; layer style to the ticks layer (I used #242424).</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.03.39 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.03.39 PM"></div><p>Add a &#8220;Drop Shadow&#8221; layer style to the ticks layer:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.04.07 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.04.07 PM"></div><p>Add a &#8220;Inner Shadow&#8221; layer style to the ticks layer:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.05.48 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.05.48 PM"></div><p>Your loader should now look like this:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 6.50.18 PM.jpg" width="281" height="230" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 6.50.18 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 2: Styling Shapes</span> Duplicating Layers</h2><p>There are a few ways we could go about this next bit, but to make things simpler we&#8217;re going to duplicate our tick layer five times, and then delete all of the shape ticks which don&#8217;t belong to those particular shape layers.  We don&#8217;t want any overlapping ticks marks from layers below, as the layer styles we&#8217;ll be adding would stack, causing over-exposed looking effects.</p><p>Duplicate your base tick layer four times, then start deleting tick marks on each of the layers until you end up with the following:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.17.51 PM.jpg" width="289" height="417" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.17.51 PM"></div><p>You can use the Direct Selection tool to delete the tick shapes from each of the layers.</p><hr
/><h2><span>Step 3: Styling Shapes</span> Style Them Puppies</h2><p>Now we&#8217;ll add some styles to each of the individual tick mark layers we separated out.  I&#8217;ll be referencing my own layer names.</p><p>To the layer named &#8220;Shine-Active&#8221;, add/modify the &#8220;Outer Glow&#8221; layer style:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.20.49 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.20.49 PM"></div><p>To the same layer, add/modify the &#8220;Inner Glow&#8221; layer style:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.20.56 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.20.56 PM"></div><p>Then add/modify the &#8220;Color Overlay&#8221; layer style (I used #0087c6):</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.20.59 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.20.59 PM"></div><p>To the layer named &#8220;Shine-Fading1&#8243;, add the exact same styles above, omitting the &#8220;Outter Glow&#8221; layer style:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.21.32 PM.jpg" width="286" height="155" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.21.32 PM"></div><p>To the layer named &#8220;Shine-Fading2&#8243;, add/modify the &#8220;Inner Shadow&#8221; layer style:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.22.18 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.22.18 PM"></div><p>To the same layer, add/modify the &#8220;Inner Shadow&#8221; layer style (I used #0087c6).</p><p>Then, to the layer named &#8220;Shine-Fading3&#8243;, add/modify the &#8220;Inner Shadow&#8221; layer style (note the change in opacity as well):</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.22.37 PM.jpg" width="598" height="453" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.22.37 PM"></div><p>Your loader should now look something like this (tweak layer styles to your liking):</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.22.54 PM.jpg" width="314" height="275" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.22.54 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 1: Animating Shapes</span> Group &amp; Duplicate</h2><p>Okay, we&#8217;ve got the base styles set up, now it&#8217;s time to duplicate the layers a whole bunch (which will make animating a snap) and create our animate .gif</p><p>Group all of the layers that make up our tick mark (highlight them all + Layer menu > Group Layers)</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.23.28 PM.jpg" width="289" height="258" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.23.28 PM"></div><p>Duplicate the entire group, then rotate it 45&deg; (Edit menu > Free Transform). Repeat Step 2 until you&#8217;ve rotated the tick mark all the way around (you&#8217;ll have eight groups in total).</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.25.53 PM.jpg" width="289" height="340" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.25.53 PM"></div><p>Your loader should look something like this:</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.26.02 PM.jpg" width="314" height="275" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.26.02 PM"></div><hr
/><h2><span>Step 2: Animating Shapes</span> Animate</h2><p>Alright, our layers are all set up, and we&#8217;re ready to animate.  We&#8217;re going to stick with regular frame by frame animation, although we could accomplish the same things with the timeline-based animation.</p><p>Open up the Animation Panel: (Window > Animation). Turn off all the tick group layers except the first one, then click the &#8220;Duplicate Selected Frames&#8221; button in the animation panel.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.26.42 PM.jpg" width="543" height="133" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.26.42 PM"></div><p>Turn off the first grouped layer, and turn on the second grouped layer.</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.26.47 PM.jpg" width="289" height="367" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.26.47 PM"></div><p>Repeat the previous step for each of the group layers. Highlight all frames in your animation layer (Shift + Click Each Frame) and set frame duration to .1 sec</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.27.38 PM.jpg" width="543" height="133" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.27.38 PM"></div><p>Choose File > Save for Web &amp; Devices and use the following settings for your animated .gif</p><div
class="tutorial_image"><img
src="http://d3pr5r64n04s3o.cloudfront.net/tuts/377_loading_gif/Screen shot 2012-09-04 at 1.28.19 PM.jpg" width="311" height="282" alt="Screen Shot 2012 09 04 At 1.28.19 PM"></div><p>Open up your .gif in a web browser and admire your new fancy loader! Lastly, get some ice cream.</p><hr
/><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>That&#8217;s it.  I hope you&#8217;ve enjoyed creating the loader!  It was fun for me to set up.  Upload and link to some of your creations in the comments, and ask any questions you may have.</p><hr
